About Lysine Lactylation
Lysine lactylation (Kla) is a recently discovered post-translational modification (PTM) where a lactate-derived lactyl group is added to a lysine residue on a protein.

This modification links cellular metabolism (specifically glycolysis) directly to protein function and gene regulation. It has been implicated in various biological processes, including inflammation, immune response, and diseases like cancer.

Predicting potential lactylation sites helps researchers identify key proteins and pathways regulated by this modification, opening new avenues for therapeutic research.

How It Works
This tool analyzes your input sequence to predict which Lysine (K) residues are likely to be lactylated.

Protein Input: The tool directly scans the protein sequence for Lysine (K) residues and analyzes the flanking amino acids.
DNA/RNA Input: The nucleic acid sequence is translated into six potential protein sequences (Open Reading Frames).
Prediction: Each frame is then analyzed individually using the selected prediction model to identify potential lactylation sites.
AGAE-Lactylation Prediction Workflow

The online tool is available: https://agae-layzer-v1.netlify.app/ & https://agae-layzer-v2.netlify.app/

